I would like to perform views precompilation in the following scenario for net core version 2.1.0-rtm-30733 targeting net461:

Solution has 2 projects:
Project A has the startup.cs class and all the logic
Project B has wwwroot and Views

project A loads project B views using:
.AddRazorOptions(options =>
                {
                    options.FileProviders.Clear();
                    options.FileProviders.Add(new PhysicalFileProvider(path to views parent folder));
                })

In this scenario in which of the projects should I add the Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Razor.ViewCompilation package and MvcRazorCompileOnPublish property and after adding it, it should work without any other changes even though its in different project?

_Copied from original issue: aspnet/MvcPrecompilation#268_

Scenario:

I have a custom `IUrlHelper`:

``` C#
public class CdnUrlHelper : UrlHelper
 {
        const string CdnContentVersion = "3.0";
        public CdnUrlHelper(IActionContextAccessor accessor, IActionSelector actionSelector)
            : base(accessor, actionSelector)
        {
        }

        public override string Content(string contentPath)
        {
            return $"//mycdn/{contentPath.Substring(1)}?_v={CdnContentVersion}";
        }
    }
```

Using a ~/ url in the app (`<link href="~/content/css" />`) fails with:

`InvalidOperationException: Unexpected return value from 'IUrlHelper.Content' for URL '~/images/ASP-NET-Banners-01.png'. If the 'IUrlHelper' service has been overridden, change 'Content' to replace only the '~/' prefix. Otherwise, add the following directive to the Razor page to disable URL resolution relative to the application's 'webroot' setting: @removeTagHelper "Microsoft.AspNet.Mvc.Razor.TagHelpers.UrlResolutionTagHelper, Microsoft.AspNet.Mvc.Razor"`

Doesn't seem like there's a way to turn off the exception.

This is a follow up to https://github.com/aspnet/Docs/issues/6278 A quest trying to figure out what is the default search path for ViewComponents

Probably I am doing something wrong, but I cannot get ViewComponent to be included in a page. 


I have a folder structure:
```
- Pages
  - Components
    - ExternalSystems
      - Default.cshtml
- Views
  - Shared
    - Components
      - ExternalSystems
        - Default.cshtml
```

within `Pages/Index.cshtml` i'v tried to include this component by trial & error (i'm learning this stuff after all):
```
@await Component.InvokeAsync("ExternalSystems");
@await Component.InvokeAsync("/Pages/Components/ExternalSystems");
@await Component.InvokeAsync("/Pages/Components/ExternalSystems/Default");
@await Component.InvokeAsync("/Pages/Components/ExternalSystems/Default.cshtml");
@await Component.InvokeAsync("/Views/Shared/ExternalSystems");
```

I expected that exception will show places searched like it does for `@Html.Partial`:
> InvalidOperationException: The partial view 'none' was not found. The following locations were searched: /Pages/none.cshtml /Views/Shared/none.cshtml

However for every single call to `@await Component.InvokeAsync` it spits this exception: `InvalidOperationException: Could not find an 'Invoke' or 'InvokeAsync' method for the view component '<Stripped.Out>.Pages.Identities.IndexModel'.`
First of all, it doesn't show me paths searched. Second, wait what? Why are you telling me something about Pages.Identities. Yes, I have that model, but it is nowhere referenced in neither `Pages/Index.cshtml` or View Component i'm trying to include.

Could someone please provide me with a guidance to determine: How view component paths are searched? For Razor Pages it is not documented, only in [3rd party site](https://www.learnrazorpages.com/razor-pages/view-components). 
Anyway it doesn't work that way for me - what would be the debugging steps? Console debug doesn't show anything useful.
